<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-691-985  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 691 985.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Dec 17 1990 v12 n51 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Publishing, drawing features merge; innovative double-dutyapplications give users many advantages. (Graphics)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coale, Kristi.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The popularity of Microsoft's Windows 3.0 graphical user interface(GUI) has encouraged the development of graphics programs thatblur the line between drawing and desktop publishing applications.andO;New graphics packages such as Micrografx Inc's Designer 3.01,Corel Systems' Corel Draw 2.0 and Computer Support Corp's Arts andLetters 3.1 incorporate such sophisticated functions as colorseparation, font handling and multi-column layout.andP;  Specialeffects let user design logos or new typefaces for advertisingapplications.andP;  Vendors say that users are demanding more featuresas awareness of Windows' power makes them more sophisticated.andP;  Allthree programs support Windows fonts and rasterizing schemes suchas Adobe Type Manager.andP;  Corel Draw 2.0 has its own internal fontrasterizer, and Computer Support Corp says it emphasizes colorseparation rather than fonts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Graphics SoftwareTrendsGraphical User InterfaceDesktop PublishingSoftware DesignSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>